webpackJsonp([0xad5ebe49339c],{471:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Jeffry.in",author:"Jeff Wainwright"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/Users/jwainwright/Dropbox/me/git-docs/yowainwright.github.io/src/pages/2017-03-12-good-commit-messages.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>For software engineers, it is easy to reach an agreement that good commit messages are important. It is equally easy to reach the agreement that most commit messages are not good. In this post, AWW, a formula for writing basic meaningful commit messages, will be discussed.</p>\n<h2>3 Things Meaningful Commit Messages Should Have</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>action</strong>: this word is a verb that describes what the commit does</li>\n<li><strong>what</strong>: word(s) that describe what the <em>action</em> is relative to</li>\n<li><strong>where</strong>: word(s) that describe <em>where</em> the <em>action</em> is happening to <em>what</em> </li>\n</ul>\n<p>This is called <strong>AWW</strong> which sounds cute, so I like it.</p>\n<p>Here’s a git terminal example:</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-bash"><code class="language-bash">git commit -m &#39;changes `dataObj.id` in the `dataObj`&#39;</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>In the example above:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>action</strong> is the word ‘changes’</li>\n<li><strong>what</strong> is <code class="language-text">dataObj.id</code></li>\n<li><strong>where</strong> is ‘in the <code class="language-text">dataObj</code>’</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Why make a formula?</h2>\n<p>Git messages are important. They seem simple to write in discussion. When changing multiple files or things in a file, the meaning of changes can be lost easily. Following the AWW formula helps composing meaning when committing. </p>',frontmatter:{featured_image:null,meta:"This post describes AWW, a formula for writing meaningful commit messages with git.",title:"AWW—A Formula For Writing Git Commits",date:"March 12, 2017",path:"/formula-for-commits/"}}},pathContext:{}}}});
